To consolidate Hong Kong's status as an Asian fintech hub, the HKMA continues to implement various measures to encourage banks and payment sectors to develop and apply technology. Key achievements this year included:
- Promoting broader usage of the fast payment system 'Faster Payment System (FPS)';
- Encouraging the banking sector to adopt open application programming interfaces (APIs);
- Connecting the trade finance platform 'TradeLink' with the People's Bank of China (PBOC)-administered blockchain-based trade finance platform to promote digital trade finance;
- Researching the application of central bank digital currencies (CBDCs) in cross-border payments;
- Exploring the feasibility of the 'Business Data Link' and researching new types of credit scoring models to help small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) obtain financing;
- Announcing a two-year plan aimed at building a more robust and diverse regulatory technology (regtech) ecosystem to further advance regtech applications;
- Strengthening talent development; and
- Advancing cross-border fintech collaboration.

The Exchange Fund Advisory Committee has established the following investment objectives for the Exchange Fund:
(a) Safeguarding capital;
(b) Ensuring that the overall money supply is fully supported by highly liquid U.S. dollar assets at all times;
(c) Guaranteeing adequate liquidity to maintain monetary and financial stability; and
(d) Seeking investment returns to the maximum extent possible while adhering to the aforementioned objectives (a) to (c) in order to protect the long-term purchasing power of the fund.

During the audit carried out in accordance with the Audit Office's audit standards, I will exercise professional judgment and maintain professional skepticism. I will also:
- Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement in the financial statements arising from fraud or error; design and perform audit procedures to address these risks; and obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence to support my opinion. Because fraud may involve collusion, forgery, deliberate omission, false representation, or override of internal control, the risk of not detecting a material misstatement resulting from fraud is higher than the risk of not detecting one resulting from error;
- Understand the internal control relevant to the audit to design appropriate audit procedures. This does not constitute an opinion on the effectiveness of the Group's internal control;
- Evaluate the appropriateness of the accounting policies adopted by the Chief Executive and the reasonableness of the accounting estimates and related disclosures made;
- Determine whether the use of the going concern assumption by the Chief Executive is appropriate, and based on the audit evidence obtained, determine whether there are material uncertainties related to events or conditions that could raise significant doubts about the Group's ability to continue as a going concern. If I believe there are material uncertainties, I must draw the attention of the users to the related disclosure in the financial statements. If the related disclosures are inadequate, I shall issue an audit report with a qualified opinion. My conclusions are based on the audit evidence obtained as of the date of the auditor's report. However, future events or circumstances may cause the Group to be unable to continue as a going concern;
- Evaluate the overall presentation, structure, and content of the financial statements, including disclosures, and whether the financial statements present fairly the transactions and events; and
- Obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence regarding the financial information of entities or business activities within the Group to express an opinion on the financial statements. I am responsible for directing, supervising, and performing the audit of the Group. I bear full responsibility for my audit opinion.

The basis of preparation of these financial statements is on the cost basis, except for the following assets and liabilities measured at fair value:
- Derivative financial instruments (Note 2.6);
- Financial assets and financial liabilities measured at fair value through profit or loss (Note 2.6);
- Financial assets measured at fair value through other comprehensive income (Note 2.6);
- Gold (Note 2.10); and
- Investment properties (Note 2.11).
